The problem asks for the supremum of admissible numbers $c$, where $c$ is admissible if any finite set $A$ of real numbers such that every subset $B$ of size 4 has $|B-B| = 11$ contains a Sidon subset $S$ of size at least $c|A|$. The condition $|B-B| = 11$ for every 4-element subset $B$ means that every 4-element subset has exactly 5 distinct positive differences. According to a result by Gyárfás and Lehel (1995), such a set $A$ must be a union of two Sidon sets. For such a set, the largest Sidon subset has size at least $n/2$, making $c=1/2$ an admissible number. Conversely, a set formed by the union of two very separated Sidon sets shows that the supremum of such $c$ is $1/2$.

